{
  "root_cause": "With SGLANG_USE_CUDA_IPC_TRANSPORT=1 but SGLANG_USE_IPC_POOL_HANDLE_CACHE disabled, each multimodal feature is sent via a per-tensor CUDA/HIP IPC handle. Under high concurrency the sender can free or recycle the backing device buffer before the scheduler process reconstructs the tensor from that handle, so the receiver dereferences a stale device pointer.",
  "fix": "Set SGLANG_USE_IPC_POOL_HANDLE_CACHE=1 in launch_qwen3.5_27b_sglang.sh. This routes multimodal tensors through the persistent MmItemMemoryPool and caches the pool-level IPC handle, so the underlying device allocation stays alive across requests and the receiver never opens a freed pointer.",
  "evidence": "From /app/crash_qwen3.5-27b-mmmu-con128.log:\n[2026-07-16 12:50:59 TP1] Failed to deserialize from CUDA IPC handle (HIP error: invalid device pointer\n  File \"/sgl-workspace/sglang/python/sglang/srt/utils/cuda_ipc_transport_utils.py\", line 488, in reconstruct_on_target_device\n  torch.AcceleratorError: HIP error: invalid device pointer\n[2026-07-16 12:50:59] SIGQUIT received. ... It usually means one child failed."
}
